A heap is a complete binary tree used mainly to get the smallest or largest element fast.

Min Heap: parent is smaller than both children
    So the minimum element is always at the root.

Max Heap: parent is larger than both children
    So the maximum element is always at the root.

Easy summary
Structure	    Used internally?
Array	            YES
ArrayList-like      dynamic array	YES
Linked List	        NO
Binary Tree nodes	NO

Operations
1) Add / Insert

    When you add a new element:

        Put it at the end of the heap.
        Then move it up until heap property is restored.

    This is called heapify up or sift up.

2) Delete / Remove root

    When you delete:

        Take the root element out.
        Move the last element to the root.
        Then move it down until heap property is restored.

    This is called heapify down or sift down.

Time complexity
Insert: O(log n)
Delete root: O(log n)
Peek root: O(1)


Java code: Min Heap and Max Heap

Min Heap
import java.util.*;

class MinHeap {
    private ArrayList<Integer> heap;

    public MinHeap() {
        heap = new ArrayList<>();
    }

    private int parent(int i) {
        return (i - 1) / 2;
    }

    private int leftChild(int i) {
        return 2 * i + 1;
    }

    private int rightChild(int i) {
        return 2 * i + 2;
    }

    public void add(int val) {
        heap.add(val);
        heapifyUp(heap.size() - 1);
    }

    private void heapifyUp(int i) {
        while (i > 0 && heap.get(i) < heap.get(parent(i))) {
            int p = parent(i);
            Collections.swap(heap, i, p);
            i = p;
        }
    }

    public int peek() {
        if (heap.isEmpty()) {
            throw new RuntimeException("Heap is empty");
        }
        return heap.get(0);
    }

    public int remove() {
        if (heap.isEmpty()) {
            throw new RuntimeException("Heap is empty");
        }

        int root = heap.get(0);
        int last = heap.remove(heap.size() - 1);

        if (!heap.isEmpty()) {
            heap.set(0, last);
            heapifyDown(0);
        }

        return root;
    }

    private void heapifyDown(int i) {
        int n = heap.size();

        while (true) {
            int smallest = i;
            int left = leftChild(i);
            int right = rightChild(i);

            if (left < n && heap.get(left) < heap.get(smallest)) {
                smallest = left;
            }

            if (right < n && heap.get(right) < heap.get(smallest)) {
                smallest = right;
            }

            if (smallest == i) {
                break;
            }

            Collections.swap(heap, i, smallest);
            i = smallest;
        }
    }

    public void printHeap() {
        System.out.println(heap);
    }
}
Max Heap
import java.util.*;

class MaxHeap {
    private ArrayList<Integer> heap;

    public MaxHeap() {
        heap = new ArrayList<>();
    }

    private int parent(int i) {
        return (i - 1) / 2;
    }

    private int leftChild(int i) {
        return 2 * i + 1;
    }

    private int rightChild(int i) {
        return 2 * i + 2;
    }

    public void add(int val) {
        heap.add(val);
        heapifyUp(heap.size() - 1);
    }

    private void heapifyUp(int i) {
        while (i > 0 && heap.get(i) > heap.get(parent(i))) {
            int p = parent(i);
            Collections.swap(heap, i, p);
            i = p;
        }
    }

    public int peek() {
        if (heap.isEmpty()) {
            throw new RuntimeException("Heap is empty");
        }
        return heap.get(0);
    }

    public int remove() {
        if (heap.isEmpty()) {
            throw new RuntimeException("Heap is empty");
        }

        int root = heap.get(0);
        int last = heap.remove(heap.size() - 1);

        if (!heap.isEmpty()) {
            heap.set(0, last);
            heapifyDown(0);
        }

        return root;
    }

    private void heapifyDown(int i) {
        int n = heap.size();

        while (true) {
            int largest = i;
            int left = leftChild(i);
            int right = rightChild(i);

            if (left < n && heap.get(left) > heap.get(largest)) {
                largest = left;
            }

            if (right < n && heap.get(right) > heap.get(largest)) {
                largest = right;
            }

            if (largest == i) {
                break;
            }

            Collections.swap(heap, i, largest);
            i = largest;
        }
    }

    public void printHeap() {
        System.out.println(heap);
    }
}
Example usage
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        MinHeap minHeap = new MinHeap();
        minHeap.add(10);
        minHeap.add(5);
        minHeap.add(20);
        minHeap.add(2);

        System.out.println("Min Heap root: " + minHeap.peek()); // 2
        System.out.println("Removed: " + minHeap.remove());      // 2
        System.out.println("New root: " + minHeap.peek());      // 5

        MaxHeap maxHeap = new MaxHeap();
        maxHeap.add(10);
        maxHeap.add(5);
        maxHeap.add(20);
        maxHeap.add(2);

        System.out.println("Max Heap root: " + maxHeap.peek()); // 20
        System.out.println("Removed: " + maxHeap.remove());      // 20
        System.out.println("New root: " + maxHeap.peek());      // 10
    }
}
Easy way to remember
Min Heap → smallest on top
Max Heap → largest on top
Add → go to end, then move up


Easy trick to remember

For node i: when in an array i starts from 0

Formula	Meaning
    2*i + 1	left child
    2*i + 2	right child
    (i-1)/2	parent

    This array actually represents a binary tree:

                50 (0)
              /        \
          30 (1)      40 (2)
          /    \      /    \
       10(3) 20(4) 35(5) 37(6)

Children formulas start with:

    2*i

    Then:

    +1 → left
    +2 → right

Formulas with 1-based indexing

For node at index i: when root index starts from i = 1

    Operation	    Formula
    Parent	         i / 2
    Left child	     2 * i
    Right child	     2 * i + 1

we imagine Index: 1 2 3 4 5 6 7

Example:
Index:   1   2   3   4   5   6   7
Value:  50  30  40  10  20  35  37

Tree:

            50(1)
          /       \
      30(2)      40(3)
      /   \      /   \
   10(4) 20(5) 35(6) 37(7)



Internally how it works
    add(x)
        Put element at the end of the internal array
        Move it up using heap logic
    poll()
        Remove root element
        Move last element to root
        Move it down using heap logic

That is exactly why:

    add() → O(log n)
    poll() → O(log n)
    peek() → O(1)


Important point
PriorityQueue does not store elements in sorted order.
It only guarantees:

    root is min element in min heap
    root is max element in max heap

The rest of the array is only heap-ordered, not fully sorted.

offer() in PriorityQueue works almost exactly like add().

    Internally both:
        insert element at the end
        do heapify up
        maintain heap property

Difference between add() and offer()
add()
    pq.add(10);
       If insertion fails : throws exception

offer()
    pq.offer(10);
        If insertion fails : returns false

But in normal PriorityQueue…

Java PriorityQueue is usually unbounded, So both behave almost the same.

PriorityQueue<Integer> pq = new PriorityQueue<>();

pq.add(10);
pq.offer(20);

System.out.println(pq);

Both insert successfully.

In heap, we store elements inside an array/list.

Example:

Index:   0   1   2   3   4   5   6
Value:  50  30  40  10  20  35  37

This array actually represents a binary tree:

            50 (0)
          /        \
      30 (1)      40 (2)
      /    \      /    \
   10(3) 20(4) 35(5) 37(6)

The numbers in brackets are indexes.

Formulas

For any node at index i:

    Parent = (i - 1) / 2
    Left child = 2 * i + 1
    Right child = 2 * i + 2

Why these formulas work

Because heap is stored level by level in array form.

Example:

            50
          /    \
        30      40
       /  \    /  \
     10  20  35  37

Stored as:

[50, 30, 40, 10, 20, 35, 37]
Code
class HeapIndexes {

    // parent index
    static int parent(int i) {
        return (i - 1) / 2;
    }

    // left child index
    static int leftChild(int i) {
        return 2 * i + 1;
    }

    // right child index
    static int rightChild(int i) {
        return 2 * i + 2;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        int i = 2;

        System.out.println("Parent index: " + parent(i));
        System.out.println("Left child index: " + leftChild(i));
        System.out.println("Right child index: " + rightChild(i));
    }
}
